# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: casb-security
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:casb-security/access-control] In physical security and information security, **access control** (**AC**) is the action of deciding whether a subject should be granted or denied access to an object (for example, a place or a resource).
[src:casb-security/access-control] The act of *accessing* may mean consuming, entering, or using.
[src:casb-security/access-control] It is often used interchangeably with authorization, although the authorization may be granted well in advance of the access control decision.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Access control on digital platforms is also termed admission control.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The protection of external databases is essential to preserve digital security.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Access control is considered to be a significant aspect of privacy that should be further studied.
[src:casb-security/access-control] **Access control policy** (also **access policy**) is part of an organization’s security policy.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In order to verify the access control policy, organizations use an access control model.
[src:casb-security/access-control] General security policies require designing or selecting appropriate security controls to satisfy an organization's risk appetite - access policies similarly require the organization to design or select access controls.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Broken access control is often listed as the number one risk in web applications.
[src:casb-security/access-control] On the basis of the "principle of least privilege", consumers should only be authorized to access whatever they need to do their jobs, and nothing more.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Geographical access control may be enforced by personnel (e.g. border guard, bouncer, ticket checker), or with a device such as a turnstile.
[src:casb-security/access-control] There may be fences to avoid circumventing this access control.
[src:casb-security/access-control] An alternative of access control in the strict sense (physically controlling access itself) is a system of checking authorized presence, see e.g.
[src:casb-security/access-control] A variant is exit control, e.g. of a shop (checkout) or a country.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The term access control refers to the practice of restricting entrance to a property, a building, or a room to authorized persons.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Physical access control can be achieved by a human (a guard, bouncer, or receptionist), through mechanical means such as locks and keys, or through technological means such as access control systems like the mantrap.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Within these environments, physical key management may also be employed as a means of further managing and monitoring access to mechanically keyed areas or access to certain small assets.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Physical access control is a matter of who, where, and when.
[src:casb-security/access-control] An access control system determines who is allowed to enter or exit, where they are allowed to exit or enter, and when they are allowed to enter or exit.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Historically, this was partially accomplished through keys and locks.
[src:casb-security/access-control] When a door is locked, only someone with a key can enter through the door, depending on how the lock is configured.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not allow restriction of the key holder to specific times or dates.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Mechanical locks and keys do not provide records of the key used on any specific door, and the keys can be easily copied or transferred to an unauthorized person.
[src:casb-security/access-control] When a mechanical key is lost or the key holder is no longer authorized to use the protected area, the locks must be re-keyed.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Electronic access control (EAC) uses computers to solve the limitations of mechanical locks and keys.
[src:casb-security/access-control] It is particularly difficult to guarantee identification (a critical component of authentication) with mechanical locks and keys.
[src:casb-security/access-control] A wide range of credentials can be used to replace mechanical keys, allowing for complete authentication, authorization, and accounting.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The electronic access control system grants access based on the credential presented.
[src:casb-security/access-control] When access is granted, the resource is unlocked for a predetermined time and the transaction is recorded.
[src:casb-security/access-control] When access is refused, the resource remains locked and the attempted access is recorded.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The system will also monitor the resource and alarm if the resource is forcefully unlocked or held open too long after being unlocked.
[src:casb-security/access-control] When a credential is presented to a reader, the reader sends the credential's information, usually a number, to a control panel, a highly reliable processor.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The control panel compares the credential's number to an access control list, grants or denies the presented request, and sends a transaction log to a database.
[src:casb-security/access-control] When access is denied based on the access control list, the door remains locked.
[src:casb-security/access-control] If there is a match between the credential and the access control list, the control panel operates a relay that in turn unlocks the resource.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The control panel also ignores an opening signal to prevent an alarm.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Often the reader provides feedback, such as a flashing red LED for an access denied and a flashing green LED for an access granted.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The above description illustrates a single factor transaction.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Credentials can be passed around, thus subverting the access control list.
[src:casb-security/access-control] For example, Alice has access rights to the server room, but Bob does not.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Alice either gives Bob her credential, or Bob takes it; he now has access to the server room.
[src:casb-security/access-control] To prevent this, two-factor authentication can be used.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In a two factor transaction, the presented credential and a second factor are needed for access to be granted; another factor can be a PIN code, a second credential, operator intervention, or a biometric input.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Passwords are a common means of verifying a user's identity before access is given to information systems.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In addition, a fourth factor of authentication is now recognized: someone you know, whereby another person who knows you can provide a human element of authentication in situations where systems have been set up to allow for such scenarios.
[src:casb-security/access-control] For example, a user may have their password, but have forgotten their smart card.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In such a scenario, if the user is known to designated cohorts, the cohorts may provide their smart card and password, in combination with the extant factor of the user in question, and thus provide two factors for the user with the missing credential, giving three factors overall to allow access.
[src:casb-security/access-control] A credential is a physical/tangible object, a piece of knowledge, or a facet of a person's physical being that enables an individual access to a given physical facility or computer-based information system.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Typically, credentials can be something a person knows (such as a number or PIN code), something they have (such as an access badge), something they are (such as a biometric feature), something they do (measurable behavioural patterns), or some combination of these items.
[src:casb-security/access-control] This is known as multi-factor authentication.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The typical credential is an access card or key-fob, and newer software can also turn users' smartphones into access devices.
[src:casb-security/access-control] There are many card technologies including magnetic stripe, bar code, Wiegand, 125 kHz proximity, 26-bit card-swipe, contact smart cards, and contactless smart cards.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Also available are key-fobs, which are more compact than ID cards, and attach to a key ring.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Biometric technologies include fingerprint, facial recognition, iris recognition, retinal scan, voice, and hand geometry.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The built-in biometric technologies found on newer smartphones can also be used as credentials in conjunction with access software running on mobile devices.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In addition to older more traditional card access technologies, newer technologies such as near-field communication (NFC), Bluetooth low energy or Ultra-wideband (UWB) can also communicate user credentials to readers for system or building access.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Access control decisions are made by comparing the credentials to an access control list.
[src:casb-security/access-control] This look-up can be done by a host or server, by an access control panel, or by a reader.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The development of access control systems has observed a steady push of the look-up out from a central host to the edge of the system, or the reader.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The predominant topology circa 2009 is hub and spoke with a control panel as the hub, and the readers as the spokes.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The look-up and control functions are by the control panel.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The spokes communicate through a serial connection; usually RS-485.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Some manufactures are pushing the decision making to the edge by placing a controller at the door.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Some readers may have additional features such as a display and function buttons for data collection purposes (i.e. clock-in/clock-out events for attendance reports), camera/speaker/microphone for intercom, or smart card read/write support.
[src:casb-security/access-control] All the RS-485-related advantages and disadvantages also apply.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The advantages and disadvantages of IP controllers apply to the IP readers as well.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The most common security risk of intrusion through an access control system is by simply following a legitimate user through a door, referred to as "tailgating".
[src:casb-security/access-control] Often, a legitimate user may hold the door for the intruder as an act of common courtesy.
[src:casb-security/access-control] This risk can be minimized through security awareness training of the user population, or more active means such as turnstiles which admit only one person at a time.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In very high-security applications, this risk is minimized by using a sally port (sometimes called a "security vestibule" or "mantrap"), where operator intervention is required, presumably after confirming valid identification.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The second most common risk is from levering a door open by sheer brute force.
[src:casb-security/access-control] This is relatively difficult on properly-secured doors with ruggedized strikes or high holding force magnetic locks.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Fully-implemented access control systems include forced-door monitoring alarms.
[src:casb-security/access-control] These vary in effectiveness, often failing from high false-positive alarms, poor database configuration, or lack of active intrusion monitoring.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Most newer access control systems incorporate some type of "door prop" alarm to inform system administrators of a door left open longer than a specified length of time.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The third most common security risk arises from natural disasters.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In order to mitigate this risk, the structure of the building, down to the quality of the network and computer equipment is crucial.
[src:casb-security/access-control] From an organizational perspective, the leadership will need to adopt and implement an All Hazards Plan, or Incident Response Plan.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The highlights of any incident plan recommended by the National Incident Management System usually include pre-incident planning, during-incident actions, disaster recovery, and after-action review.
[src:casb-security/access-control] An attack similar to levering is breaking through cheap partition walls, typically made of wallboard or cinder blocks.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In shared tenant spaces, the divisional wall is a vulnerability.
[src:casb-security/access-control] A vulnerability along the same lines is the breaking of sidelight windows located next to doors.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Spoofing of locking hardware is fairly simple and more elegant than levering.
[src:casb-security/access-control] A strong magnet can operate the solenoid controlling bolts in electric locking hardware.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Motorized locks, more prevalent in Europe than in the US, are also susceptible to this attack using a doughnut-shaped magnet.
[src:casb-security/access-control] It is also possible to manipulate the power to the lock either by removing or adding current, although most Access Control systems incorporate battery back-up systems, and the locks are almost always located on the secure side of the door.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Access cards themselves have proven vulnerable to sophisticated attacks.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Enterprising hackers have built portable readers that capture the card number from a user's proximity card.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The hacker simply walks by the user, reads the card, and later presents the number to a reader securing the door.
[src:casb-security/access-control] This is possible when card numbers are sent in the clear, no encryption being used.
[src:casb-security/access-control] To counter this, dual authentication methods, such as a card plus a PIN should always be used.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Many access control credentials use unique serial numbers which are programmed in sequential order during manufacturing.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In a method known as a "sequential attack", if an intruder has a credential once used in the system, they can simply increment or decrement the serial number until they find a credential that is currently authorized in the system.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Specifying credentials with random unique serial numbers is recommended to counter this threat.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In addition, increasingly long lockout timeout intervals after a credential failure will make automated repeated attacks infeasible.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Finally, most electric locking hardware still uses mechanical keys as a fail-over.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Most conventional mechanical key locks are vulnerable to bumping.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In computer security, general access control includes authentication, authorization, and audit.
[src:casb-security/access-control] A more narrow definition of access control would cover only access approval, whereby the system makes a decision to grant or reject an access request from an already authenticated subject, based on what the subject is authorized to access.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Authentication and access control are often combined into a single operation, so that access is approved based on successful authentication, or based on an anonymous access token.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Authentication methods and tokens include passwords, biometric analysis, physical keys, electronic keys and devices, hidden paths, social barriers, and monitoring by humans and automated systems.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In any access-control model, the entities that can perform actions on the system are called *subjects*, and the entities representing resources to which access may need to be controlled are called *objects* (see also Access Control Matrix).
[src:casb-security/access-control] Subjects and objects should both be considered as software entities, rather than as human users: any human users can only have an effect on the system via the software entities that they control.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In some models, for example the object-capability model, any software entity can potentially act as both subject and object.
[src:casb-security/access-control] As of 2014, access-control models tend to fall into one of two classes: those based on capabilities and those based on access control lists (ACLs).
[src:casb-security/access-control] Both capability-based and ACL-based models have mechanisms to allow access rights to be granted to all members of a *group* of subjects (often the group is itself modeled as a subject).
[src:casb-security/access-control] Access to accounts can be enforced through many types of controls.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Discretionary Access Control (DAC) In DAC, the data owner determines who can access specific resources.
[src:casb-security/access-control] For example, a system administrator may create a hierarchy of files to be accessed based on certain permissions.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Graph-based Access Control (GBAC) Compared to other approaches like RBAC or ABAC, the main difference is that in GBAC access rights are defined using an organizational query language instead of total enumeration.
[src:casb-security/access-control] History-Based Access Control (HBAC) Access is granted or declined based on the real-time evaluation of a history of activities of the inquiring party, e.g. behavior, time between requests, content of requests.
[src:casb-security/access-control] For example, the access to a certain service or data source can be granted or declined on the personal behavior, e.g. the request interval exceeds one query per second.
[src:casb-security/access-control] History-of-Presence Based Access Control (HPBAC) Access control to resources is defined in terms of presence policies that need to be satisfied by presence records stored by the requestor.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Policies are usually written in terms of frequency, spread and regularity.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Identity-Based Access Control (IBAC) Using this network administrators can more effectively manage activity and access based on individual needs.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Lattice-Based Access Control (LBAC) A lattice is used to define the levels of security that an object may have and that a subject may have access to.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The subject is only allowed to access an object if the security level of the subject is greater than or equal to that of the object.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Mandatory Access Control (MAC) In MAC, users do not have much freedom to determine who has access to their files.
[src:casb-security/access-control] For example, security clearance of users and classification of data (as confidential, secret or top secret) are used as security labels to define the level of trust.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Organization-Based Access Control (OrBAC) OrBAC model allows the policy designer to define a security policy independently of the implementation.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Relationship-Based Access Control (ReBAC) A subject's permission to access a resource is defined by the presence of relationships between those subjects and resources.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) RBAC allows access based on the job title.
[src:casb-security/access-control] RBAC largely eliminates discretion when providing access to objects.
[src:casb-security/access-control] For example, a human resources specialist should not have permissions to create network accounts; this should be a role reserved for network administrators.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Rule-Based Access Control (RAC) RAC method, also referred to as Rule-Based Role-Based Access Control (RB-RBAC), is largely context based.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Example of this would be allowing students to use labs only during a certain time of day; it is the combination of students' RBAC-based information system access control with the time-based lab access rules.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Responsibility Based Access Control Information is accessed based on the responsibilities assigned to an actor or a business role.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Subscription-Based Access Control (SBAC) SBAC assigns permissions based on a user's subscription status, automating the process of granting, modifying, or revoking access as users subscribe, upgrade, downgrade, or cancel.
[src:casb-security/access-control] SBAC is particularly relevant for SaaS business, where access to features, data, or services is tied to a user's active plan.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Unlike RBAC or ABAC, which define permissions based on roles or attributes, SBAC dynamically distributes roles and policies based on billing status, ensuring real-time access alignment.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Several regulatory frameworks impose specific access control requirements on organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The HIPAA Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to implement technical access controls for electronic protected health information (ePHI), including unique user identification, emergency access procedures, automatic logoff, and encryption and decryption mechanisms.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The proposed HIPAA Security Rule update (NPRM, December 2024) would strengthen these requirements by mandating multi-factor authentication for all access to ePHI.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The Payment Card Industry Data Security Standard (PCI DSS) Requirement 7 mandates that access to cardholder data be restricted on a need-to-know basis, while Requirement 8 requires unique identification for each person with computer access.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) addresses access control extensively in Special Publication 800-53 through the AC (Access Control) control family, which includes policies for account management, separation of duties, least privilege, and session controls.
[src:casb-security/access-control] A technique used to define or restrict the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data onto, a storage device.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The definition or restriction of the rights of individuals or application programs to obtain data from, or place data into, a storage device.
[src:casb-security/access-control] The process of limiting access to the resources of an AIS (Automated Information System) to authorized users, programs, processes, or other systems.
[src:casb-security/access-control] That function performed by the resource controller that allocates system resources to satisfy user requests.
[src:casb-security/access-control] This definition depends on several other technical terms from Federal Standard 1037C.
[src:casb-security/access-control] Special public member methods – **accessors** (aka **getters**) and **mutator methods** (often called **setters**) are used to control changes to class variables in order to prevent unauthorized access and data corruption.
[src:casb-security/access-control] In public policy, access control to restrict access to systems ("authorization") or to track or monitor behavior within systems ("accountability") is an implementation feature of using trusted systems for security or social control.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] A **cloud access security broker** (**CASB**) (sometimes pronounced cas-bee) is on-premises or cloud based software that sits between cloud service users and cloud applications, and monitors all activity and enforces security policies.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] A CASB can offer services such as monitoring user activity, warning administrators about potentially hazardous actions, enforcing security policy compliance, and automatically preventing malware.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] CASBs deliver security and management features.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] Broadly speaking, "security" is the prevention of high-risk events, whilst "management" is the monitoring and mitigation of high-risk events.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] CASBs that deliver security must be in the path of data access, between the user and the cloud provider.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] Architecturally, this might be achieved with proxy agents on each end-point device, or in agentless fashion without configuration on each device.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] Agentless CASBs allow for rapid deployment and deliver security on both company-managed and unmanaged BYOD devices.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] Agentless CASB also respect user privacy, inspecting only corporate data.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] Agent-based CASBs are difficult to deploy and effective only on devices that are managed by the corporation.
[src:casb-security/cloud-access-security-broker] Agent-based CASBs typically inspect both corporate and personal data.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:casb-security/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Data loss incidents (unauthorized disclosure or deletion of sensitive data) may turn into data leak incidents (data breaches) when media containing sensitive information are lost and then acquired by an unauthorized party, including via data theft.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] However, a data leak is possible without losing the data on the originating side.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] There are limitations to the effectiveness of DLP systems in reducing risk of data loss.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Technological means for prevention data loss include standard security measures, advanced/intelligent security measures, access control and encryption, and content-aware DLP systems, although only the latter category is typically referred to as DLP.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Most DLP systems rely on predefined rules to identify and categorize sensitive information.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Standard security measures, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems (IDSs), and antivirus software, are widely used to guard against both outsider and insider attacks.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Intrusion detection systems identify unauthorized use, misuse, and abuse of computer systems by monitoring for behavior patterns that differ from legitimate users.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Advanced security measures employ machine learning, behavioral analytics, honeypots, temporal reasoning, and activity-based verification to detect abnormal or unauthorized data access patterns.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Machine learning algorithms enable systems to automatically improve through experience, identifying patterns in large datasets to enhance detection capabilities.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Content-aware DLP systems detect and prevent unauthorized attempts to copy, transmit, or publish sensitive data.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] These systems use mechanisms such as exact data matching, structured data fingerprinting, statistical methods, rule-based detection, and contextual analysis.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Network (data in motion) systems operate at egress points and analyze traffic for sensitive information being transmitted in violation of policy.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Next-generation firewalls and intrusion detection systems often support DLP-like capabilities.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Endpoint (data in use) systems monitor user actions on desktops, servers, and devices, enabling controls such as blocking copying, printing, screen capture, or unauthorized email transmission.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Cloud DLP monitors data within cloud services and applies controls to enforce access and usage policies.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Cloud computing provides on-demand network access to shared computing resources, enabling scalable and flexible data protection strategies.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] These systems help maintain compatibility with existing on-premises DLP infrastructure while addressing issues that are unique to cloud environments such as shared responsibility models, multi-cloud data governance, and shadow IT discovery.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Data identification techniques classify information as structured or unstructured.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Roughly 80% of enterprise data is unstructured.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Recent industry guidance describes data classification and policy alignment as foundational elements of effective DLP programs.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Vendors also emphasize the role of integrated DLP, analytics, and automation in modern data protection strategies.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Data distributors may intentionally or unintentionally share data with third parties, after which it is later found in unauthorized locations.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP investigations attempt to determine the source.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP techniques include access controls, encryption, and data retention policies.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Data encryption transforms readable information into an unreadable format to protect confidentiality, ensuring only authorized parties with the proper decryption key can access the original data.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] "Data in use" refers to data currently being accessed.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP systems may monitor and flag unauthorized manipulation or transfer of such data.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] "Data in motion" refers to data traveling across internal or external networks.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP systems monitor and control this flow.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] False positive management remains a significant issue.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Policies that are too broad tend to generate alerts that require manual review which may overwhelm security teams and reduce the overall effectiveness of DLP software.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Privacy and compliance concerns can arise when an organization monitors employees.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Achieving data security in such situations requires a delicate balance between adequate monitoring and taking care that individual privacy rights are not infringed upon.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Evasion techniques exist including steganography, encryption, or manipulation of a file's format that can sometimes circumvent DLP detection methods and require continuous updating of detection software.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] The complexity of DLP policy increases substantially in global organizations due to their greater size and operation in disparate jurisdictions.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP software in these cases must often contend with more diverse regulatory requirements, a broader range of data types, and relatively complex business processes.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] This makes it challenging to achieve consistent enforcement across regions and departments.
[src:casb-security/data-loss-prevention-software] Relevant information privacy laws include the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), HIPAA in the United States, and the California Consumer Privacy Act.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] In organizations, **shadow IT** refers to information technology (IT) systems deployed by departments other than the central IT department, to bypass limitations and restrictions that have been imposed by central information systems.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] While it can promote innovation and productivity, shadow IT introduces security risks and compliance concerns, especially when such systems are not aligned with corporate governance.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] Information systems in large organizations can be a source of frustration for their users.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] In order to bypass limitations of solutions provided by a centralized IT department, as well as restrictions that are deemed detrimental to individual productivity, non-IT departments might develop independent IT resources for their own specific or urgent need or requirements.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] With a personal computer, *PC Magazine* said in 1984, "now every executive's secretary or assistant bookkeeper can bang out in 20 minutes what once took a team of MIS specialists 2 days to accomplish".
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] In some cases, IT specialists could be recruited or software solutions procured outside of the centralized IT department, sometimes without the knowledge, or approval of corporate governance channels.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] Although often perceived as attempts to undermine corporate governance, the existence of shadow IT often is an indicator of needs from individual departments not being satisfied from a centrally managed information ecosystem.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] Shadow IT increases the likelihood of uncontrolled data flows, making it more difficult to comply with various legislations, regulations or sets of best practices.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] Within an organization, the amount of shadow IT activity is by definition unknown, especially since departments often hide their shadow IT activities as a preventive measure to ensure their ongoing operations.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] Even when figures are known, organizations are reluctant to voluntarily admit their existence.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] As a notable exception, The Boeing Company has published an experience report describing the number of shadow applications which various departments have introduced to work around the limitations of their official information system.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] According to Gartner, by 2015, 35 percent of enterprise IT expenditures for most organizations will be managed outside the central IT department's budget.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] A 2026 survey by American cybersecurity company Vanta found that 70 percent of companies have shadow IT, with employees adopting AI tools without full security reviews or IT oversight.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] The report noted that large language models (LLMs) are more likely to be flagged as a security risk than traditional software-as-a-service applications.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] The issue extends to employee behavior, with the report documenting instances of employees reinstalling AI tools after IT departments have revoked access.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] The most commonly used applications identified were ChatGPT, Claude, and Cursor.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] Security risks arise when data or applications move outside protected systems, networks, physical location, or security domains.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] BankAmerica employees began deploying personal computers within the company in late 1981.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] While the financial firm already extensively used large computers, as the data processing budget did not account for personal computers, individual employees and offices bought them and expensed them as office supplies.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] After the purchasing department in summer 1982 discovered unusually large purchases from Computerland stores, Bank of America allotted an acquisition budget for small computers and standardized on the IBM PC.
[src:casb-security/shadow-it] By early 1983 all executives including president Sam Armacost reportedly had IBM PCs.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS products typically run on rented infrastructure as a service (IaaS) or platform as a service (PaaS) systems including hardware and sometimes operating systems and middleware, to accommodate rapid increases in usage while providing instant and continuous availability to customers.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS customers have the abstraction of limitless computing resources, while economy of scale drives down the cost.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS architectures are typically multi-tenant; usually they share resources between clients for efficiency, but sometimes they offer a siloed environment for an additional fee.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Common SaaS revenue models include freemium, subscription, and usage-based fees.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Unlike traditional software, it is rarely possible to buy a perpetual license for a certain version of the software.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] There are no specific software development practices that distinguish SaaS from other application development, although there is often a focus on frequent testing and releases.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) is the most basic form of cloud computing, where infrastructure resources—such as physical computers—are not owned by the user but instead leased from a cloud provider.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] As a result, infrastructure resources can be increased rapidly, instead of waiting weeks for computers to ship and set up.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] IaaS requires time and expertise to make use of the infrastructure in the form of operating systems and applications.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Platform as a service (PaaS) includes the operating system and middleware, but not the applications.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS providers typically use PaaS or IaaS services to run their applications.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Without IaaS, it would be extremely difficult to make an SaaS product scalable for a variable number of users while providing the instant and continual availability that customers expect.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Most end users consume only the SaaS product and do not have to worry about the technical complexity of the physical hardware and operating system.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Because cloud resources can be accessed without any human interactions, SaaS customers are provided with the abstraction of limitless computing resources, while economy of scale drives down the cost.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Another key feature of cloud computing is that software updates can be rolled out and made available to all customers nearly instantaneously.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] In 2019, SaaS was estimated to make up the plurality, 43 percent, of the cloud computing market while IaaS and PaaS combined account for approximately 25 percent.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] In the 1960s, multitasking was invented, enabling mainframe computers to serve multiple users simultaneously.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Over the next decade, timesharing became the main business model for computing, and cluster computing enabled multiple computers to work together.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Cloud computing emerged in the late 1990s with companies like Amazon (1994), Salesforce (1999), and Concur (1993) offering Internet-based applications on a pay-per-use basis.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] All of these focused on a single product to seize a high market share.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Beginning with Gmail in 2004, email services were some of the first SaaS products to be mass-marketed to consumers.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The market for SaaS grew rapidly throughout the early twenty-first century.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Initially viewed as a technological innovation, SaaS has come to be perceived more as a business model.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] By 2023, SaaS had become the primary method that companies deliver applications.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Popular consumer SaaS products include all social media websites, email services like Gmail and its associated Google Docs Editors, Zoom, Dropbox, and entertainment products like Netflix and Spotify.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Enterprise SaaS products include Salesforce's customer relationship management (CRM) software, SAP Cloud Platform, and Oracle Cloud Enterprise Resource Planning.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Some SaaS providers offer free services to consumers that are funded by means such as advertising, affiliate marketing, or selling consumer data.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] One of the most popular models for Internet start-ups and mobile apps is freemium, where the company charges for continued use or a higher level of service.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Even if the user never upgrades to the paid version, it helps the company capture a higher market share and displace customers from a rival.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] However, the company's hosting cost increases with the number of users, regardless of whether it is successful at enticing them to use the paid version.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Another common model is where the free version only provides demonstration (crippleware).
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Online marketplaces may charge a fee on transactions to cover the SaaS provider costs.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] It used to be more common for SaaS products to be offered for a one-time cost, but this model is declining in popularity.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] A few SaaS products have open source code, called open SaaS.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] This model can provide advantages such as reduced deployment cost, less vendor commitment, and more portable applications.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The most common SaaS revenue models involve subscription and pay for usage.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] For customers, the potential advantages include reduced upfront cost, increased flexibility, and lower overall cost compared to traditional software with perpetual software licenses.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] In some cases, the steep one-time cost demanded by sellers of traditional software were out of the reach of smaller businesses, but pay-per-use SaaS models make the software affordable.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Usage may be charged based on the number of users, transactions, amount of storage spaced used, or other metrics.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Many buyers prefer pay-per-usage because they believe that they are relatively light users of the software, and the seller benefits by reaching occasional users who would otherwise not buy the software.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] However, there are also many buyers who prefer perpetual licenses for reasons such as, high subscription prices, and subscription fatigue.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] It can also cause revenue uncertainty for the seller and increases the overhead for billing.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The subscription model of SaaS offers a continuing and renewable revenue stream to the provider, although vulnerable to cancellation.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] If a significant number are cancelled, the viability of the business can be placed in jeopardy.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The ease of canceling a subscription and switching to a competitor leave customers with the leverage to get concessions from the seller.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] While recurring revenues can help the business and attract investors, the need for customer service skills in convincing the customer to renew their subscription is a challenge for providers switching to subscription from other revenue models.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The Rule of 40 is a commonly used metric by investors to evaluate SaaS company performance, calculated as the sum of revenue growth rate and EBITDA margin (with a target combined score of 40% or above).
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS products are typically accessed via a web browser as a publicly available web application.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] This means that customers can access the application anywhere from any device without needing to install or update it.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS providers often try to minimize the difficulty of signing up for the product.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Many capitalize on the service-oriented structure to respond to customer feedback and evolve their product quickly to meet demands.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] This can enable customers to believe in the continued improvement of the product and help the SaaS provider get customers from an established traditional software company that likely can offer a deeper feature set.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Although on-premises software is often less secure than SaaS alternatives, security and privacy are among the main reasons cited by companies that do not adopt SaaS products.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS companies have to protect their publicly available offerings from abuse, including denial-of-service attacks and hacking.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] They often use technologies such as access control, authentication, and encryption to protect data confidentiality.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Nevertheless, not all companies trust SaaS providers to keep sensitive data secured.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The vendor is responsible for software updates, including security patches, and for protecting the customers' data.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS systems inherently have a greater latency than software run on-premises due to the time for network packets to be delivered to the cloud facility.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] This can be prohibitive for some uses, such as time-sensitive industrial processes or warehousing.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The rise of SaaS products is one factor that has led many companies to shift IT budgets from capital expenditure to operating expenditure.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The process of migration to SaaS and supporting it can also be a significant cost that must be accounted for.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] A challenge for SaaS providers is that demand is not known in advance.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Their system must have enough slack to be able to handle all users without turning any away, but without paying for too many resources that will be unnecessary.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] If resources are static, they are guaranteed to be wasted during non-peak time.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Sometimes cheaper off-peak rates are offered to balance the load and reduce waste.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The expectation for continuous service is so high that outages in SaaS software are often reported in the news.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] There are no specific software development practices that differentiate SaaS from other types of application development.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS products are often released early and often to take advantage of the flexibility of the SaaS delivery model.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Agile software development is commonly used to support this release schedule.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Many SaaS developers use test-driven development, or otherwise emphasize frequent software testing, because of the need to ensure availability of their service and rapid deployment.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Domain-driven design, in which business goals drive development, is popular because SaaS products must sell themselves to the customer by being useful.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS developers do not know in advance which devices customers will try to access the product from—such as a desktop computer, tablet, or smartphone—and supporting a wide range of devices is often an important concern for the front-end development team.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Progressive web applications allow some functionality to be available even if the device is offline.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS applications predominantly offer integration protocols and application programming interfaces (APIs) that operate over a wide area network.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS architecture varies significantly from product to product.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Nevertheless, most SaaS providers offer a multi-tenant architecture.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] With this model, a single version of the application, with a single configuration (hardware, network, operating system), is used for all customers ("tenants").
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] This means that the company does not need to support multiple versions and configurations.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The architectural shift from each customer running their own version of the software on their own hardware affects many aspects of the application's design and security features.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] In a multi-tenant architecture, many resources can be used by different tenants or shared between multiple tenants.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The structure of a typical SaaS application can be separated into application and control planes.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS products differ in how these planes are separated, which might be closely integrated or loosely coupled in an event- or message-driven model.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The control plane is in charge of directing the system and covers functionality such as tenant onboarding, billing, and metrics, as well as the system used by the SaaS provider to configure, manage, and operate the service.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Many SaaS products are offered at different levels of service for different prices, called tiering.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] This can also affect the architecture for both planes, although it is commonly placed in the control plane.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Unlike the application plane, the services in the control plane are not designed for multitenancy.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The application plane—which varies a great deal depending on the nature of the product—implements the core functionality of the SaaS product.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Key design issues include separating different tenants so they cannot view or change other tenants' data or resources.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Except for the simplest SaaS applications, some microservices and other resources are allocated on a per-tenant basis, rather than shared between all tenants.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Routing functionality is necessary to direct tenant requests to the appropriate services.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Some SaaS products do not share any resources between tenants—called siloing.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Although this negates many of the efficiency benefits of SaaS, it makes it easier to migrate legacy software to SaaS and is sometimes offered as a premium offering at a higher price.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Pooling all resources might make it possible to achieve higher efficiency, but an outage affects all customers so availability must be prioritized to a greater extent.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Many systems use a combination of both approaches, pooling some resources and siloing others.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Other companies group multiple tenants into pods and share resources between them.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] SaaS architecture typically allows users to access applications through a web browser without installing software on their local devices.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] This approach simplifies software maintenance and updates, as service providers can manage the application centrally.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] It also enables organizations to scale services easily according to their needs.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] In the United States, constitutional search warrant laws do not protect all forms of dynamically stored SaaS data.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] The result is that governments may be able to request data from SaaS providers without the owner's consent.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] Certain open-source licenses such as GPL-2.0 do not explicitly grant rights permitting distribution as a SaaS product in Germany.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] In 2026, with the emergence of generative AI tools, multiple SaaS companies saw a steep fall in stock market price.
[src:casb-security/software-as-a-service] February 3 saw a US $300 billion loss of value, in a crisis coined the "SaaS-Pocolypse".
